y-login/\">Theme Your Login Page</a></p>\n<p>There is a plugin that does this extremely well, which is why we didn&#8217;t include the functionality in PMPro itself. <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/theme-my-login/\">The plugin is Theme My Login</a>. Activate that plugin and visit the settings page to setup your login page to show up on the front end just like ours. TML has some other great &#8220;modules&#8221; which can be activated to do some other things important in membership sites, like themeing the profile page or redirecting users to a certain page when logged in.</p>\n<p>2. <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/wp-hide-admin\">Hide the Dashboard From Non-admins</a></p>\n<p>The plugin you want here is called <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/wp-hide-admin\">WP Hide Dashboard</a>, and it does just that. It will redirect any non-admin away from the dashboard.</p>\n<p>3. <a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/hide-admin-bar-from-non-admins.zip\">Hide the Admin Bar from Non-admins</a></p>\n<p>The plugins above don&#8217;t hide the admin bar, which you often want to hide as well. There are some plugins in the WP repo to hide the admin bar, but they either (a) hide it for admins as well or (b) require users to disable the bar via their settings. We whipped up our own plugin hide the admin bar for non-admins only. I should put this in the WP repo (or email the Hide Admin Bar folks with a tweak), but for now you can <a href=\"/wp-content/uploads/hide-admin-bar-from-non-admins.zip\">download a zip file to install our hide-admin-bar-from-non-admins</a>.</p>\n<p>Let me know if you have any other ideas. I have a list of common functions that membership site owners typically need to do and will be working to include all of that information in the documentation here on the site.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10